User survey for ImagingSociety 2025 - National MRI research infrastructure in Norway

Author

Dr. Athanasia M. Mowinckel

Published

September 26, 2025

Background

This report presents an analysis of the survey data collected for the national grant scheme application for MRI research infrastructure in Norway. The survey was designed to gather insights from the research community on the current use, needs, and challenges related to MRI for human research.

The following sections will present a summary of the key findings, including graphical representations of the quantitative data and a textual summary of the open-ended responses, with the help of the Gemini LMM.

Survey Results

Of the 54 responses, 24 participants reported they currently use MRI for research, 44% indicate a future interest in using the new MRI facility for their work.

Participant Demographics

This section provides an overview of the survey participants’ roles and institutions.

Research Areas

Based on the survey responses, the dominant research areas are:

  • Cognitive Neuroscience: This is the most frequently mentioned area, encompassing various subfields like music cognition, language, attention, decision-making, and predictive processing.

  • Neuroscience: A broad category, also heavily represented, encompassing areas like affective, social, and political neuroscience, integrative neuroscience, and general neuroscience research.

  • Mental Health: Research focusing on various mental disorders like psychosis, mood disorders, anorexia nervosa, and general mental health including child and adolescent psychiatry.

  • Neurological Disorders: Research on various neurological conditions, including Multiple Sclerosis, dementia, Alzheimer’s Disease, stroke, brain tumors, and neurodegenerative diseases.

Other notable research areas mentioned include:

  • Aging: Studies related to healthy aging, dementia, and age-related cognitive decline.
  • Brain Injury: Including brain injury in sports and rehabilitation medicine.
  • Imaging Techniques: Research involving MRI, multimodal imaging, and other neuroimaging techniques.
  • Women’s Health: Topics like sexual health, body image, menopause, and menstrual cycle related issues.
  • Clinical Psychology

In summary, the survey respondents are primarily engaged in research within the fields of cognitive neuroscience, neuroscience, mental health, and neurological disorders, with a significant emphasis on brain imaging techniques and aging related research.

How MRI Would Enhance Research

These survey responses overwhelmingly indicate that increased and improved access to MRI would significantly expand and enhance the research capabilities of the respondents across a wide range of fields. Here’s a summary of the key themes:

  • Enabling New Research Directions: Many researchers highlighted that access to MRI would allow them to explore completely new research areas, particularly those requiring detailed brain imaging and function data (e.g., sexual dysfunction, non-invasive brain stimulation, and menstrual health).
  • Improving Existing Research: Respondents in fields such as neurology, dementia, bilingualism, pain, mental health, musculoskeletal, oncology, cognition, and neurosurgery emphasized that MRI is already crucial to their work, and better access would improve the quality, depth, and efficiency of their existing studies.
  • Enhancing Study Design and Power: Reliable access to MRI would allow for better planning, execution, and statistical power in studies, particularly for those investigating complex neurological processes.
  • Facilitating Multi-Center Collaboration: Increased access would enable participation in larger, multi-center studies, particularly beneficial for research on rare or specific patient populations, and research on populations that are located farther from current MRI capabilities.
  • Supporting Translational Research: Several respondents mentioned the importance of MRI in bridging the gap between basic research and clinical applications, including diagnosis, treatment monitoring, and the development of new interventions.
  • Addressing Limitations of Current Access: Many researchers expressed that current limited and unpredictable MRI access constrains their research progress, necessitating data collection outside their institutions or even outside the country. Barriers also include: costs, limited access to MRI slots, and lack of neuroradiologists to support MRI research.
  • Supporting Training and Skill Development: Access to MRI would enable researchers to gain experience and expertise in neuroimaging, improving their competitiveness for funding and collaboration.
  • Driving Innovation: Some researchers would like to develop novel MRI sequences to suit specific research purposes.
  • Overall Impact: The responses collectively suggest that improved MRI access would lead to more innovative research, more accurate diagnostics, and more effective treatments across a diverse spectrum of medical and scientific fields.

Future Needs

This section analyzes which conditions are considered most important for the future of MRI research in Norway.

Summary of Free-text Comments

This section provides a summary of the open-ended comments, generated using the Gemini LMM.

Overall, the responses express strong enthusiasm for the MRI research initiative, with several recurring themes. A key desire is to enhance research accessibility and collaboration. This includes advocating for dedicated research scanners, ideally located outside of hospital environments and closer to university campuses to foster innovation. Participants highlight the importance of prioritizing research use and securing competitive pricing. Building a collaborative MRI research community, particularly in Tromsø, and ensuring consistent capabilities across different sites are seen as crucial. The potential for population-level mapping through synchronized scanners at multiple locations, drawing inspiration from initiatives like the UK Biobank, is also emphasized. Maintaining open communication and opportunities for involvement in future applications are also requested.

Conclusion

In conclusion, the results of this survey resoundingly underscore a critical need for increased investment in dedicated research-focused MRI scanners across Norway. The diverse perspectives and experiences shared by researchers from universities, hospitals, and other institutions paint a clear picture of the challenges posed by limited access, scheduling constraints, and scanner capabilities. The potential benefits of enhanced MRI infrastructure are substantial, ranging from boosting ongoing projects to unlocking entirely new avenues of investigation in crucial fields like neuroscience, mental health, and cancer research. This survey provides compelling evidence that strategic investment in research MRI technology is not merely a desirable improvement, but a vital necessity for advancing Norwegian scientific discovery and innovation, ultimately leading to improved healthcare outcomes and a stronger research landscape.
